<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF Diversity Week to Feature Racism Expert, Workshops, Heritage Festival</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Tom Evelyn
		
		<span class="date">Oct. 8, 2004</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:vking@mail.ucf.edu">Valarie Greene King</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6479</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.diversity.ucf.edu/">UCF Diversity Initiatives</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Spelman College President Beverly Daniel Tatum, a psychologist who has studied racism and its effects in the classroom, will speak Monday, Oct. 11, at the kickoff breakfast for the University of Central Floridas Diversity Week. </p><p /><p /><p>The 12th annual celebration, with a theme of Living the Vision, also will feature daily workshops and panel discussions and will conclude with the Indigenous Heritage Festival. Featured speakers include poet Cornelius Eady and author Michelle Malkin. </p><p /><p /><p>This weeklong event was designed to provide opportunities to explore various histories, cultures and issues of our local, national and world communities, said Valarie Greene King, director of Diversity Initiatives at UCF. From its inception, a primary focus during Diversity Week has been the promotion of communication and social justice as strategies to build a better world for humankind. </p><p /><p /><p>Tatum, a clinical psychologist whose areas of research include black families in white communities and racial identity in teens, has taught a course on the psychology of racism for more than 20 years. She has served as the president of Spelman, a historically black college for women in <city /><place />Atlanta</place /></city />, since 2002. </p><p>Tatum is the author of Why Are All the Black Kids Sitting Together in the Cafeteria? And Other Conversations About Race and Assimilation Blues: Black Families in a White Community. </p><p /><p /><p>She will speak at <time hour="8" minute="0" />8 a.m.</time /> in the Pegasus Grand Ballroom in the Student Union. The event is sold out, but media are welcome to attend. </p><p /><p /><p>Eady, the author of six books of poetry and the co-founder of Cave Canem, a summer workshop retreat for African-American poets, will speak at <time hour="19" minute="30" />7:30 p.m.</time /> Wednesday, Oct. 13, in the Pegasus Grand Ballroom. </p><p /><p /><p>Malkin, a syndicated columnist and Fox News commentator, will speak at <time hour="15" minute="0" />3 p.m.</time /> Thursday, Oct. 14, in the Pegasus Grand Ballroom. She is the author of Invasion: How America Still Welcomes Terrorists, Criminals, and Other Public Menaces to Our Shores and In Defense of Internment: The Case for Racial Profiling in World War II and the War on Terror. </p><p>Eady and Malkins talks are free and open to the public. </p><p /><p /><p>Diversity Week will conclude with the Indigenous Heritage Festival from <time hour="10" minute="0" />10 a.m.</time /> to <time hour="19" minute="0" />7 p.m.</time /> Saturday, Oct. 16, at the Student Union. This free, inaugural event will bring together indigenous peoples of the world to reach out to the <place />Central Florida</place /> community, according to the organizers. </p><p /><p /><p>For more information on Diversity Week and a complete schedule, go to <a href="http://www.diversity.ucf.edu/">www.diversity.ucf.edu </a>. </p>
		
	
